Optimising excited-state pathways in our chromophores has enabled their translation from molecular photophysics into **photoactive materials and technologies**. Across multiple dye families, controlled formation of charge-transfer and triplet states provides a practical route to designing systems that convert light into a useful and measurable output—emission, reactive species, or polymerisation—depending on the target application.

### Selected application areas

**Fluorescent probes and imaging.**  
Development of advanced probes including highly sensitive singlet-oxygen reporters, FLIM readouts of microenvironmental changes in cancer tissues, and systems with enhanced two-photon absorption for deeper-tissue imaging.

**Triplet–triplet annihilation upconversion (TTA-UC).**  
NIR-absorbing systems converting 700–800 nm excitation into visible emission (overall quantum yields up to 4%), oxygen-resistant formulations with integrated oxygen scavenging, and “dual-performance” dyes that act as sensitiser or emitter depending on the medium. *(read more: /academic/pages/tta-uc-general)*

**Photomedicine and theranostics.**  
Porphyrin-based platforms capable of generating, storing, and thermally releasing singlet oxygen, as well as heavy-atom-free, water-soluble SOCT-ISC photosensitisers for clinically relevant PDT/theranostic contexts. *(read more: /academic/pages/pdt-general and /academic/pages/singlet-oxygen)*

**Photopolymerisation and holography.**  
Green-light-activatable photoinitiators and holographic recording materials delivering high diffraction efficiencies (up to 98% in optimised systems), refractive-index modulation, and sensitivities comparable to commercial photopolymers.
